  "title": "Intersubjective Mirror",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "458788cc94cd8b16",
      "text": "BRÅTEN, Stein, 2009. The intersubjective mirror in infant learning and evolution of speech. Amsterdam ; Philadelphia: John Benjamins Pub. Advances in consciousness research, v. 76. ISBN 978-90-272-5212-8. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ca9da3ca67ce45d6",
      "text": "In the last three decades or so a number of findings have contributed to a paradigmatic shift in our understanding of the nature, neurosocial support and cultural nurture of human capacities in early infancy and children’s steps to speech. This has also invited questions about the sociocultural evolution and phylogenetic origins of prespeech and proto-conversation: When and how may precursory spoken languages have emerged? What can computer simulations of language evolution tell us, and what may we learn from primate studies? How is it that infants so soon after birth become so efficient in their speech perception and sociocultural learning? What is the path from infant imitation and simulation of body movements to children’s absorption in narratives and reading of other minds?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b283cba04d2858fa",
      "text": "In the present book on the evolution and development of (pre)verbal intersubjectivity, replies are offered in the light of recent infancy research and the [[Mirror Neurons]] discovery, studies of early speech perception, comparative primate studies, computer simulations of language evolution and imitation, and an early model of simulation of mind in conversation partners."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e21f74de0501b715",
      "text": "Laying out the background for questions about phylogeny and findings on ontogeny, Part I begins by pointing out the curious co-incidence that about the same time – 1921, 1922, 1923 – three seminal thinkers raised somewhat related questions about the nature of language and our relation to the world and others in it, while coming out with replies that differed. They were [[Martin Buber]], [[George Herbert Mead]], and [[Ludwig Wittgenstein]]. Complementing one another, they point in other directions than the seminal contributions by Freud and Piaget which were also published in the first quarter of the last century. The latter came to dominate the view of children’s nature until almost the turn of the century when empirical infancy research and the mirror neurons discovery came to invite a paradigmatic shift. For example, infant learning by (m)other-centred participation which may be observed in human infancy and is probably backed up by a mirror system enabling such perceptual reversal, illustrates the very reverse of the egocentricity attributed as point of departure for child development by Piagetian traditions. While infant capacities for such learning by imitation, to be specified in Part III, are dependent upon cultural nurture, they suggest an innate foundation in the form of an adapted resonating system afforded by phylogeny and sociocultural evolution."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "82367930f78d0aba",
      "text": "⇒ [[Mirror Neurons]]"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "7df0ab20c2297aa2",
      "text": "> (Q) In which epoch of hominid evolution would an adapted resonant mirror system enabling distant learning by virtual participation in the activity of adult models have afforded the most critical selective advantage? (Bråten 2002:274)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e55dd94beb2c919f",
      "text": "A speculative reply is ventured in part II, partly based on my comparative observations of infant-adult interaction in humans and in chimpanzees. In the latter connection I am indebted to Edward Moseid and Kristiansand Zoo and Wildlife Park (in the Southern Part of Norway) for opening their doors for my observations of chimpanzee and offspring interaction. My observations began in 1992 when one of the chimpanzee mothers there saved her previously near-rejected infant from suffocation and after that became a holding mother in Winnicott’s sense. This is recounted in Chapter 5, and as illustrated there, I have records not just of infants clinging to their mothers, but of offspring carrying their younger siblings, when allowed by the watching mother. It is striking how the infant, clinging to the mother’s back, not only moves with her movements, but usually also adjusts the head to the mother’s head direction, and thus appears to gaze in the same direction as the mother’s gaze. Deprived of this advantage of protective and nurturing carrying and clinging, I submit, those hominid infants and parents who had the compensating capacity to [[warn]] and listen to warning signals and to teach and learn to cope by altercentric participation in the other, would come to have a critical selective advantage. This presupposes an adapted mirror systems allowing for perceptual reversal in face-to-face situations (which subjects with autism find difficult, returned to in Chapter 11)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5c241d6bb85d63d9",
      "text": "We were given the opportunity to pursue such implications of the mirror neurons discovery at the symposium on “Mirror neurons and the Evolution of Brain and Language”, in Delmenhorst, July 2000, resulting in proceedings with the same title by Stamenov and Gallese (Eds 2002). And then, proceedings of the Theory Forum symposium in Oslo, October 2004, on Foundations of (pre)verbal intersubjectivity in light of new findings, resulted in the collective volume On Being Moved: From Mirror Neurons to Empathy (Ed. Bråten 2007), constitute another pertinent source volume for the present book. In conjunction with the predecessor, the proceedings of the first Theory Forum symposium on Intersubjective Communication and Emotion in Early Ontogeny (Ed. Bråten 1998), they afford basis for much of Part III, devoted to children’s steps from neonatal imitation to conversation and mind-reading."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3c161debb8682cce",
      "text": "Beginning with primary intersubjectivity as defined by [[Colwyn Trevarthen]] (1979), and the senses of self (and other) as distinguished by [[Daniel Stern]] (1985/2000), these intersubjective steps in speech acquisition and conversational development in ontogeny is outlined in Chapter 3. Here is emphasized Stern’s ‘staircase-logic’, by which each lower layer continues to be operative and support higher-order layers. This is the same logic that we apply in distinguishing the steps from primary to higher order tertiary intersubjectivity in ontogeny (Bråten & Trevarthen 1994/2000, 2007). They permit a halting comparison with the cultural transitions in evolution as posited by Donald (1991), giving rise to questions about phylogeny pursued in Part II."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5270cfe7cc5b6daf",
      "text": "Chapter 4 opens with questions about language evolution and phylogenesis of imitative learning, and with descriptions of a number of connectionist models and computer simulation runs by which researchers have pursued such questions in artificial conditions from a varied set of assumptions – including whether or not Darwinian assumptions about natural selection may have been at play in (pre)linguistic evolution. Some connectionist models described concern the kind of mirror neurons support and adaptation required for perception and imitation in face-to-face situation of such apparently simple acts as observing and re-enacting arm-raising or a hand sign, and which actually require a radical frame of reference shift entailing perceptual reversal."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e7c3eb6317325eff",
      "text": "This pertains to the hominin infant decentration hypothesis followed up in Chapter 5, concerning a phylogenetic basis for efficient cultural learning – in particular of gestural and (pre)speech language – from examining the role that this critical difference between hominin infants and offspring of other primates may have played: While offspring of other primates can cling by own force to the body of their quadrupedal mothers and enjoy the instructive and protective advantages of thus being carried around, infants of bipedal hominin mothers deprived of this advantage in order to survive would have to critically depend on communication from a distance by gestural and sound signals mediating warning and instructions. And what is more, much of this would have to occur in face-to-face interaction."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5f386ebf0ace4d35",
      "text": "Chapter 6 examines some episodes of prosocial behaviour in great apes and toddlers. Some significant chimpanzee episodes of helping others have been reported by [[Frans de Waal]]. In the middle of the last century [[Anna Freud]] reported with her co-researchers some beautiful examples of altruistic behaviours by toddlers in wartime nursing homes and by three-year olds rescued from Nazi concentration camps. And, then there are my documentations of 11-month-old girls who reciprocate their caregivers’ spoon-feeding and even share the sweet dessert with their caregivers."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a20fc6f8af751d73",
      "text": "As will be turned to in detail in Chapter 8, before their first year’s birthday infants are able to reciprocate the spoon-feeding to which they have been subjected, and even reveal by their mouth-movements that they take a virtual part in the other’s intake of food. Such occurrences will be accounted for in terms of a ‘virtual other’ mechanism (Bråten 1986/1988) operating as an altercentric resonant mirror system enabling the infant to feel a virtual moving with alter’s feeding movements from alter’s stance, leaving the infant with a procedural memory of having been a virtual co-author of the feeding, guiding the subsequent reciprocating re-enactment. This is learning by altercentric participation, defined as imitational learning by Ego’s virtual participation in Alter’s act from Alter’s stance as if Ego had been facing the same direction or been hand-guided giving rise to shared temporal vitality (affects) contours, reflecting the manner in which the enactment is felt to be virtually co-enacted and the feeling that directs the co-enactment, enabling circular re-enactment from procedural memory of such virtual co-enactments. The term ‘vitality contours’ is [[Daniel N. Stern]]’s (1999) term for such jointly experienced feelings that specify the movement contour, in contrast to discrete emotions. Consistently, the procedural memory left by such virtual co-enactment is here termed ‘e-motional memory’ (from the root sense ‘out-of-motion’ and the folk sense of ‘being moved by’). In face-to-face learning situations this entails sensorimotor reversal of what has been seen done by the other – entailing a shift from the other-centred frame of reference entailing resonance with what the model has been doing, to the self-centred frame of reference required for execution of the re-enactment, i.e., a shift from altercentric to egocentric body co-ordinates."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ae2a1b1f5966d138",
      "text": "As for my prediction that neural cells or a neural system supporting such altercentric participant perception would be discovered, an impetus was afforded by [[John O’Keefe]] at a King’s College Research Centre Workshop on the perception of subjects and objects in Cambridge, September 1992. Here, referring to evidence of so called ‘place cells’, he raised the issue of the relation between egocentric [[maps]] and allocentric maps in animals retrieving hidden foods. In conjunction with my virtual other postulate and with Trevarthen’s having posited an alteroceptive capacity in infants (as a complement to their proprioceptive capacity), here were afforded stepping stones for my later identification of altercentric participation. At the Cambridge workshop, upon my presentation of the minimal organizational prerequisites for the formation of schematic means for simulating the other, the theory of mind advocate [[Jean Heal]] asked me whether I regarded the modes of felt immediacy and simulational mediacy to be mutually exclusive. I replied then in the positive. Today, in line with the intersubjective “staircase” outlined in Figure 3.1 and specified in the Part III, I would have been more nuanced in my reply: while verbal conversation (at the second order layer of tertiary intersubjectivity) occurs in representational mediacy and may entail reflective mind-reading, it may evoke also more empathic simulation of mind. And, then, that would clearly be supported by the underlying mode of felt immediacy, operative at the layer of primary intersubjectivity."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3ff99b51082de1b8",
      "text": "Part III is based on findings about the child’s intersubjective steps to speech and simulation of conversation partners’ mind and narrative contexts, afforded inter alia by infancy research, studies of early speech perception, and studies of children’s conversation, private speech, and understanding of others’ (mis)understanding. The sequence of the various chapters in this part adheres to these distinctions of primary, secondary and tertiary intersubjectivity:"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "58872721e16736af",
      "text": "[…]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4c870527a0e763c2",
      "text": "When there is a biological impairment of the altercentric capacity, as turned to in Chapter 11, this is inter alia reflected in difficulties in gestural imitation in face-to-face situations. For example, when subjects with autism are asked to “Do as I do” and understand the invitation, they have difficulties in matching the model’s gesture, incapable of carrying out the required perceptual mirror reversal entailed by altercentric participant perception. Simple examples are raising arms, grasp thumb, or peck-a-boo (cf. Bråten 1998a; Whiten & Brown 1998). In this connection I thank [[Peter Hobson]] for his recent acknowledgment of my explanatory prediction of perceptual mirror reversal deficit in autism which I voiced in July and August 1994, respectively in Paris and Oslo."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ff9521f12e847313",
      "text": "The question about [[perceptual reversal]] as one of the topics for future research is returned to in the concluding chapter, concerned also with how the above intersubjective steps pertain to caregiver guidance. In connection with my lecture at a Marte Meo conference in 2002 and preparation for another one at a forthcoming International Child Development Program (ICDP) event I appreciate the informative manuals and material given me, respectively, by [[Maria Aarts]] and by [[Karsten Hundeide]], both of whom I was fortunate to meet in Bergen in the late 1980’s during my stay there as an invited guest professor in cognitive science."
