      "id": "a20fc6f8af751d73",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "a20fc6f8af751d73",
        "text": "As will be turned to in detail in Chapter 8, before their first year’s birthday infants are able to reciprocate the spoon-feeding to which they have been subjected, and even reveal by their mouth-movements that they take a virtual part in the other’s intake of food. Such occurrences will be accounted for in terms of a ‘virtual other’ mechanism (Bråten 1986/1988) operating as an altercentric resonant mirror system enabling the infant to feel a virtual moving with alter’s feeding movements from alter’s stance, leaving the infant with a procedural memory of having been a virtual co-author of the feeding, guiding the subsequent reciprocating re-enactment. This is learning by altercentric participation, defined as imitational learning by Ego’s virtual participation in Alter’s act from Alter’s stance as if Ego had been facing the same direction or been hand-guided giving rise to shared temporal vitality (affects) contours, reflecting the manner in which the enactment is felt to be virtually co-enacted and the feeling that directs the co-enactment, enabling circular re-enactment from procedural memory of such virtual co-enactments. The term ‘vitality contours’ is [[Daniel N. Stern]]’s (1999) term for such jointly experienced feelings that specify the movement contour, in contrast to discrete emotions. Consistently, the procedural memory left by such virtual co-enactment is here termed ‘e-motional memory’ (from the root sense ‘out-of-motion’ and the folk sense of ‘being moved by’). In face-to-face learning situations this entails sensorimotor reversal of what has been seen done by the other – entailing a shift from the other-centred frame of reference entailing resonance with what the model has been doing, to the self-centred frame of reference required for execution of the re-enactment, i.e., a shift from altercentric to egocentric body co-ordinates."
